SM satisfies the accidental release prevention program requirements of the RMP.  
Some of the many, specific safety features to prevent a chemical accident include:
? Computerized process control systems on chlorosilane and methyl chloride chemical reaction and purification systems to ensure that any deviations from the intended operating conditions are immediately identified and corrected;
? Instrumentation and safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error which could lead to a storage tank overfill;
? Secondary containment dikes around storage tanks and loading stations to contain a spill.
? Hydrogen chloride and methyl chloride gas sensors to detect and warn of a release.
? Extensive safety information about the processes reviewed with employees and contractors;
? Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions and safety shut down instructions;
? Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistently safe work practices;
? Maintenance programs to ensure ongoing equipment reliability and integrity - includes equipment testing and inspection;
? A management of change procedure which requires the review of proposed plant modifications for possible hazards before the change is implemented;
? Safety pre-qualification for all contractors;
? Safety reviews prior to startup of our processes; and,
? Safety systems and procedures that control hazards during special operations such as welding.
 GE Silicones is engaged in an aggressive and comprehensive effort to identify and address Year 2000 issues.  We are in the process of inventorying our equipment at the site, interviewing suppliers, putting into place corrective actions where necessary, and developing a contingency plan. We are on track to complete this process prior to critical roll-over dates and believe we have addressed the systems and equipment necessary for safe site operation.
